column5:
15 pages, no figures, Manuscript submitted to the 2nd International
  Conference on Negative CO2 Emissions, June 14-17, 2022, Gothenburg, Sweden;
  Version 3 revises the estimated global sequestration rate

column11:
  For $n\geq 4$, let $(\mathbb{R}^n, e^{2u}|dx|^2)$ be a complete even
dimensional manifold with nonnegative $Q$ curvature and $Q_ge^{nu}\in
L^1(\mathbb{R}^n)$ . Suppose $C_0e^{-|x|^{\beta}}\leq Q_g(x)$ at infinity for
some $\beta\in (0,2)$, then
  \begin{align*}
  \alpha:=\frac{1}{c_n}\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}Q_g(y)e^{nu(y)}dy\leq 1
  \end{align*}
  and
  \begin{align*}
  \chi(\mathbb{R}^n)-\frac{1}{c_n}\int_{\mathbb{R}^n}Q_g(y)e^{nu(y)}dy=\lim_{r\to\infty}\frac{|\partial
B_r(0)|_g^{\frac{n}{n-1}}}{n\omega_{n-1}^{\frac{1}{n-1}}
  | B_r(0)|_g
  },
  \end{align*}
  where $c_n=2^{n-2}\left(\frac{n-2}{2}\right)!\pi^{n/2}$ ,
$\omega_{n-1}=|\mathbb{S}^{n-1}|$. In fact, the lower bound of $Q_g$ is sharp.
Moreover, if $Q_g$ also satisfies $Q_g(x)\leq C_0|x|^{\gamma}$ at infinity for
some $\gamma>0$, then $u(x)=-\alpha\log|x|+o(\log|x|)$.
